gh their jobs can also buffer strains at home, and some of what young people learn on the job--not least responsibility and confidence--gives them an advantage in later work life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aSchool-to-work transitionzUnited StatesvLongitudinal studies. 0aYouthxEmploymentzUnited StatesvLongitudinal studies. 0aYouthxEmploymentzUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aYouthzUnited StatesxAttitudesvLongitudinal studies. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Developmental / Child.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674041240zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674041240423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674041240/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK